	In single player mode even though there is more than one human
player in a game, only a single display is opened for the current
player based on the current players DISPLAY environment variable
value.  If this player has units to move he can move them, save the
game and mail the save.xconq file to the next player allowing for a
mail version of xconq.  In this single player mode the messages
sent to players are saved in files named: <player>.not.  These
files can be mailed along with the save.xconq file to other
players.

	Starting the game with the -S option is similar to starting
the game with the -r option.  Specify the value of the DISPLAY
environment variable each player will have when starting the game on
the command line, including one for the person starting the game.  If
the display value is unknown a dummy value with the persons name can
be used and when the actual person starts his turn he will get the
unknown player prompt and be able to select the proper side as 
described bellow.

	If during the game a person's DISPLAY variable changes.  (i.e.
they move to a new machine or a dummy value was used starting the
game) When they start the game they will get a prompt indicating that
the DISPLAY value isn't in the saved game and ask them to select their
side.  This person should select the side they have been playing as.
This will update his new DISPLAY value in the save.xconq file for that
side when he saves the game.

	In this version each person must have a unique DISPLAY value.
Only one person can have a "local:0.0" value. And two people can't
play on the same host unless one uses local:0.0 and the other the
actual name. Or there is some other unique alias for the host to use
for each player.

